covered: Valid Request: Happy-path and parameterized success cases are covered (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC18) verifying 200 and JSON array of Account objects.
Empty Response: No-results and empty-database behavior tested (TC04, TC05) returning an empty JSON array with 200.

Query Parameters: Individual and combined query parameter behavior tested (offset, limit, accountWithBalance, accountWithBalanceAndCBA, audit=FULL/MINIMAL and default), including combinations (TC02, TC03).
Input Validation / Error Handling: Invalid searchKey, malformed pagination values, invalid booleans/enums covered (TC06, TC07, TC08) with expected 4xx responses.
Authentication: Missing and invalid token cases covered (TC09, TC10) returning 401.
Service & Dependency Failures: System down, timeouts and dependent-service failures covered (TC11, TC16, TC19) with 5xx expectations.
Security: SQL injection and XSS attack vectors are explicitly tested (TC12, TC13).
Performance & Concurrency: Large-volume and concurrent request scenarios are present (TC15) including a response-time expectation.
Edge / Regression / Integration: Regression for empty searchKey (TC17), extra/unexpected query params ignored (TC14), and accessibility/structure guidance (TC20).
gaps: Caching Behavior: No tests assert caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or conditional GET behavior (If-None-Match -> 304).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests exercising rate limits (429) or Retry-After header under high-frequency requests; concurrency test does not verify throttling behavior.
Schema & Content-Type Validation: Response Content-Type (application/json) and full validation against the Account JSON schema are not asserted (field types, required fields, formats).

Pagination defaults & boundary cases: Default pagination semantics (limit default = 100, offset default = 0) are not explicitly validated; boundary conditions like limit=0, very large limit/offset, and offset beyond result set are not tested.
Deterministic ordering for pagination: No tests verify stable/specified ordering across pages (no duplicates/missing records between pages).
Authorization granularity (403): Tests cover 401 (missing/invalid token) but not 403 (forbidden / insufficient privileges) if applicable.

URL-encoding / Unicode / path-encoding: While malicious payloads are tested, normal-but-special characters (spaces, +, %20, slashes, non-ASCII/unicode) and their URL-encoding/decoding behaviors are not covered.

Partial dependency failures / graceful degradation: No tests for partial failures where some account enrichments (balance/audit) succeed and others fail; only full dependency-unavailable cases are covered.
recommendations: Add caching tests: assert Cache-Control and ETag headers; add conditional GET tests using If-None-Match and expect 304 when appropriate.
Add rate-limiting tests: fire a high rate of requests to assert 429 responses and Retry-After header, and verify behavior under sustained load.

Add response schema validation: assert Content-Type: application/json and validate each Account object against the canonical Account JSON schema (types, required fields, numeric formats for balance/CBA).
Explicitly test pagination defaults and boundaries: verify default limit=100 and offset=0 behaviors, test limit=0, extremely large limit/offset, and offset beyond dataset returns empty page.
Add pagination ordering tests: create deterministic data and verify ordering is stable across pages (no duplicates/missing items), and that page offsets/limits produce expected slices.
Add URL-encoding and Unicode tests: search keys with spaces, slashes, percent-encoded characters, and non-ASCII characters to ensure correct handling and status codes.
Add finer-grained auth tests: if the endpoint enforces RBAC, add 403 tests for insufficient privileges and validate error payloads.
Test partial dependency failures: simulate dependent service returning partial results or timeouts for enrichment calls (balance/audit) and verify graceful degradation or per-account error handling.
Explicitly test audit=NONE and parameter precedence/conflict cases (e.g., conflicting boolean flags) to remove ambiguity.
